mistake.. .as White now has to face a better version of French Defence here.}
c5 $1 {Delaying the development of the flexible 'c8' bishop... Black
concentrates on taking space on the queen side for the time being.} 3. f4 {To
create a pawn chain in the centre - this move is obvious.} Nc6 $1 {Again delay.
.. Black is smartly waiting for White's king side knight to come to the f3
square.} 4. Nf3 Bg4 {This is the time to develop the flexible piece.} 5. Be2 e6
{You can see; only after developing the c8 bishop, Black plays e6...)} 6. O-O
c4 {Creating space on c5 for his bishop and increasing pressure on White's
camp by occupying the d3 and b3 squares!} 7. d4 cxd3 8. Qxd3 Bc5+ 9. Kh1 Nge7 {
Black converted to a French-like position with his extra bishop on g4!! I hope
you know that, in the French Defence, this g4 bishop is usually lying idle on
its original square 'c8'.} 10. c3 Nf5 $5 (10... O-O $1 {Accurate choice and
our recommended move in this variation. We should complete the development in
opening before implementing any plan.} 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 Nf5 13. Qd2 Qb6
$15 {Black's queen is dominating the key central diagonal, all his pieces are
in active position, his rooks are already connected, he has a very strong
centre... on the other hand, White suffers from lack of development and his
pieces are not in ideal positions; again, his king is in a sort of stalemate
position!}) 11. b4 Bb6 12. b5 Bxf3 $6 {Black missed an opportunity to take the
lead; again, it's not the proper time to exchange this strong bishop for the
knight unless it has been a forced move.} (12... Na5 $1 {This simple
forwarding move helps Black in two ways: firstly, it opens up the 'c' file for
