{This next game was played between two amateurs who committed lots of mistakes.
Still, I need to consider it to present it before you for the sake of the
importance of the opening theory.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 {Another plus point of
this move is that many players don't prepare it by considering it a dubious
opening for Black! And they are soon out of the theory after only a few moves.}
3. Bb5+ Bd7 $1 {Better than Nbd7, since White is forced to take a decision now
which is good for Black.} 4. Be2 (4. Bc4 $5 {Also quite possible; you may see
the 'theory section' for this variation.}) 4... Nxd5 {There is no reason to
ignore the 'd5' centre pawn at this moment.} 5. d4 Bf5 $1 {Important move -
develop the bishop before you play e6.} 6. c4 $6 {Too optimistic! Breaking the
golden rule - "Trust but verify". White assumes that Black's knight will go to
b6 or f6; but in reality it will not happen in this case, because there is no
pawn at a3.} (6. a3 $5 {Please see theory section.}) 6... Nb4 $1 {This is the
main drawback of White's previous move; when you attack something it shouldn't
advance!} 7. Na3 $8 (7. Qa4+ $2 {Also fails due to...} N8c6 $1 8. d5 Nc2+ 9.
Kf1 Nxa1 10. Na3 e6 11. dxc6 b6 $17 {Black is clearly ahead...}) 7... e5 $1 {
This thematic Scandinavian breakthrough works well here.} 8. dxe5 $2 (8. d5 $5
{Sensible} Bc5 9. Nf3 Nd7 $15 {Black holds the position very well without any
problems at all.}) 8... Qxd1+ {Typical Scandinavian queen exchange. You may
imagine why it is different to other gambits. Even after the queen exchange,
Black is better in the endgame due to his activity.} 9. Bxd1 Nd3+ {This knight
starts paralysis in White's camp} 10. Ke2 Nxe5 (10... Bxa3 $5 {Also
considerable...} 11. bxa3 Nxe5 12. Nf3 Nbc6 $17) 11. Nb5 Bd6 $6 {A miss from
Black's side...} (11... Bd3+ $1 {Ignoring idea, 'if you can attack, then do it
before you defend'.} 12. Ke3 Bc5+ {All White's pieces, including king, are not
in ideal position. On the contrary, all of Black's army is in aggressive mood;
Black technically wins here.} 13. Kf4 Ng6+ 14. Kg3 Na6 $17) 12. Ba4 Nbc6 13.
Bf4 $6 (13. Nxd6+ $5 cxd6 14. Nf3 Bd3+ 15. Ke3 Bxc4 $15) 13... O-O $6 (13...
Bd3+ $1 {In spite of many mistakes from both sides, Black had finally got an
opportunity to lead from a dominant position.} 14. Kd1 Bxc4 15. Nxd6+ cxd6 $17
{with a very good position for black...}) 14. Nxd6 cxd6 15. b3 Rfe8 16. Kf1 $4
(16. Be3 $1 Bd3+ 17. Kd2 Be4 $36 {Back is slightly better.}) 16... Bd3+ 17. Ne2
Bxe2+ $4 (17... Ng4 $1 {Simple win for Black.} 18. Re1 Rxe2 19. Rxe2 Re8 $19)
18. Kxe2 Nxc4+ 19. Kf3 N4e5+ 20. Kg3 Re6 21. h3 a6 22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. Rac1 Rc8
24. Rhd1 f6 25. Rd4 g5 26. Bd2 h5 27. h4 g4 28. Bb4 c5 29. Rd5 Kf7 30. Bd2 Kg6
31. Kf4 c4 32. Bb4 Nd3+ 33. Rxd3 cxd3 34. Rxc8 Re2 35. Rc1 Rxf2+ 36. Kg3 Rxa2
37. Bxd6 Rb2 38. b4 Rb3 39. Rd1 Kf5 40. Kf2 Ke4 41. g3 Rb2+ 42. Ke1 f5 43. Rd2
Rb1+ 44. Rd1 Rb2 45. Ra1 Re2+ 46. Kf1 Kf3 47. Bc5 f4 48. Ra3 Ke4 49. Rxa6 fxg3
